SENATE BILL DRS15272-MH-109A
Short Title: Revise Dam Safety Requirements. (Public)
Sponsors: Senators Lazzara, Sawyer, and Johnson (Primary Sponsors).
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO CLARIFY THE EMERGENCY ACTION PLAN REQUIREMENTS FOR
3 CERTAIN DAMS.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1. G.S. 143-215.31(a1) reads as rewritten:
6 "(a1) The owner of a dam classified by the Department as a high-hazard dam or an
7 intermediate-hazard dam shall develop an Emergency Action Plan for the dam as provided in this
8 subsection:
9 (1) The owner of the dam shall submit a proposed Emergency Action Plan for the
10 dam within 90 days after the dam is classified as a high-hazard dam or an
11 intermediate-hazard dam to the Department and the Department of Public
12 Safety for their review and approval. The Department and the Department of
13 Public Safety shall approve the Emergency Action Plan if they determine that
14 it complies with the requirements of this subsection and will protect public
15 health, safety, and welfare; the environment; and natural resources.
16 (2) The Emergency Action Plan shall include, at a minimum, all of the following:
17 a. A description of potential emergency conditions that could occur at
18 the dam, including security risks.
19 b. A description of actions to be taken in response to an emergency
20 condition at the dam.
21 c. Emergency notification procedures to aid in warning and evacuations
22 during an emergency condition at the dam.
23 d. A downstream inundation map depicting areas affected by a dam
24 failure and sudden release of the impoundment. A downstream
25 inundation map prepared pursuant to this section does not require
26 preparation by a licensed professional engineer or a person under the
27 responsible charge of a licensed professional engineer unless the dam
28 is associated with a coal combustion residuals surface impoundment,
29 as defined by G.S. 130A-309.201.The requirement to prepare a
30 downstream inundation map as part of an Emergency Action Plan does
31 not apply to a dam that is less than 15 feet in height or that has an
32 impoundment capacity of less than 50 acre-feet, unless the
33 Commission finds the Department has demonstrated that site-specific
34 factors warrant the inclusion of a downstream inundation map in the
35 Emergency Action Plan.
*DRS15272-MH-109A*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2a) A downstream inundation map prepared as part of an Emergency Action Plan
2 under subdivision (2) of this section does not require preparation by a licensed
3 professional engineer or a person under the responsible charge of a licensed
4 professional engineer unless the dam is associated with a coal combustion
5 residuals surface impoundment, as defined by G.S. 130A-309.201.
6 (3) The owner of the dam shall update the Emergency Action Plan annually and
7 shall submit it to the Department and the Department of Public Safety for their
8 review and approval within one year of the prior approval.
9 (4) The Department shall provide a copy of the Emergency Action Plan to the
10 regional offices of the Department that might respond to an emergency
11 condition at the dam.
12 (5) The Department of Public Safety shall provide a copy of the Emergency
13 Action Plan to all local emergency management agencies that might respond
14 to an emergency condition at the dam.
15 (6) Information included in an Emergency Action Plan that constitutes sensitive
16 public security information, as provided in G.S. 132-1.7, shall be maintained
17 as confidential information and shall not be subject to disclosure under the
18 Public Records Act. For purposes of this section, "sensitive public security
19 information" shall include Critical Energy Infrastructure Information
20 protected from disclosure under rules adopted by the Federal Energy
21 Regulatory Commission in 18 C.F.R. § 388.112."
22 SECTION 2. This act becomes effective July 1, 2025, and applies to Emergency
23 Action Plans required to be submitted or updated on or after that date.
